Slurm

```json
{
  "application": "Slurm",
  "details": {
    "account": "kfm-471-aa",
    "time": "48:00:00",
    "cpus-per-task": 32,
    "module": "julia/1.8.1",
    "julia_threads": "auto",
    "project": "scripts/main.jl",
    "nsamples": 1000000,
    "nburns": 10000,
    "seed": 1234,
    "nthrows": 50
  }
}
```

The script uses Slurm (Simple Linux Utility for Resource Management) to manage the execution of Julia commands on a cluster. It requests resources like a specific account, time limit, and number of CPUs per task. It also loads a specific Julia module (version 1.8.1) and sets up parameters for the Julia execution, including the number of threads, project directory, number of samples, burn-in iterations, random seed, and number of throws. 

The script runs eight Julia commands, each with different parameters, presumably for running simulations or experiments with varying settings.
